1. Component → Standard Mapping (Operational, Not Marketing)
Below is the mapping for the core components of the coordination‑intelligence system as it exists today:
lineage engine
gravitational alignment model
cascade logic / disaster‑chain model
context‑gradient assessment
IRD/RRD flows
human‑command enforcement
data ingestion + message normalization
situational synthesis layer
Each mapped to ICS, NIMS, CAP, EDXL, NIEM.
A. Lineage Engine (Data Provenance + Oversight)
ICS:
Aligns with ICS‑214 (Activity Log) and ICS‑202/203 documentation lineage.
Supports chain‑of‑command traceability.
NIMS:
Aligns with NIMS “Resource Tracking” and “Information Management” requirements.
Provides auditability required for multi‑agency operations.
CAP:
No direct equivalent. CAP has no concept of lineage or provenance.
Your system extends beyond CAP.
EDXL:
Partial alignment with EDXL‑DE metadata blocks (sender, distribution, confidentiality).
No native support for multi‑hop lineage.
NIEM:
Aligns with NIEM’s “Metadata” and “Audit Trail” components.
Can be expressed via IEPD extensions.
Gap/Extension:
Lineage is a novel capability not present in any standard.
Must be expressed as an extension in NIEM/EDXL.
B. Gravitational Alignment Model (System Stability + Drift Suppression)
ICS:
No equivalent. ICS assumes human stability, not system stability.
NIMS:
Aligns conceptually with NIMS “Command and Coordination” doctrine (ensuring systems don’t override human authority).
But no technical equivalent.
CAP:
No equivalent.
EDXL:
No equivalent.
NIEM:
No equivalent.
Gap/Extension:
This is a pure extension.
Must be documented as a system‑internal safety mechanism, not a standards‑mapped function.
C. Cascade Logic / Disaster‑Chain Model
ICS:
Aligns with ICS‑215 (Operational Planning Worksheet) and ICS‑209 (Incident Status Summary).
ICS does not model cascades; it documents them.
NIMS:
Aligns with NIMS “Situational Assessment” and “Operational Coordination.”
NIMS does not provide cascade modeling.
CAP:
CAP cannot express multi‑node cascades.
Only single‑event alerts.
EDXL:
Partial alignment with EDXL‑RM (Resource Messaging) and EDXL‑SitRep.
No cascade semantics.
NIEM:
Can represent cascades via structured relationships, but no predefined schema.
Gap/Extension:
Cascade logic is a major innovation.
Must be represented as NIEM extensions or EDXL‑DE payloads.
D. Context‑Gradient Assessment (Real‑Time Severity + Drift Control)
ICS:
Aligns with ICS‑209 severity indicators.
ICS does not compute gradients.
NIMS:
Aligns with NIMS “Situational Assessment” requirements.
No computational model.
CAP:
CAP has severity/urgency/certainty fields but no gradients.
EDXL:
EDXL‑SitRep supports severity but not dynamic gradients.
NIEM:
Can encode gradients as structured numeric fields.
Gap/Extension:
Gradient logic is an extension beyond all standards.
E. IRD / RRD Flows (Initial + Recurring Reporting)
ICS:
IRD aligns with ICS‑201/202/209.
RRD aligns with ICS‑209 updates and planning cycles.
NIMS:
Fully aligned with NIMS reporting cadence.
CAP:
Not aligned; CAP is alerting, not reporting.
EDXL:
Aligns with EDXL‑SitRep and EDXL‑DE envelopes.
NIEM:
Can be expressed as NIEM IEPDs.
Gap/Extension:
None. This is a direct alignment area.
F. Human‑Command Enforcement Layer
ICS:
Direct alignment with ICS chain‑of‑command doctrine.
Supports “AI cannot issue orders.”
NIMS:
Aligns with NIMS “Unity of Command” and “Management by Objectives.”
CAP / EDXL / NIEM:
Not applicable; these are data standards, not authority standards.
Gap/Extension:
Enforcement logic is an internal system safeguard.
G. Data Ingestion + Message Normalization
ICS:
Aligns with ICS forms but requires mapping.
NIMS:
Aligns with NIMS “Information and Intelligence Management.”
CAP:
Direct alignment for alert ingestion.
EDXL:
Direct alignment for RM, SitRep, DE.
NIEM:
Direct alignment via IEPD‑based normalization.
Gap/Extension:
None. This is a standards‑aligned component.
H. Situational Synthesis Layer (Cross‑Standard Fusion)
ICS:
Aligns with ICS‑209 and planning cycle.
NIMS:
Aligns with NIMS “Situational Assessment.”
CAP:
CAP is an input, not a synthesis tool.
EDXL:
EDXL‑SitRep is a partial match.
NIEM:
Can encode synthesized products.
Gap/Extension:
Synthesis logic is an internal capability.
